{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 401\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 51\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|03|26|df=US}}, there are 267 confirmed cases and 3 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Mayor Bowser's office announced 1 more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \u201cessential,\u201d along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser\u2019s chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \u201cbecause construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\u201d<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 401\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = 51\n| deaths          = 9\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|03|26|df=US}}, there are 267 confirmed cases and 3 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Mayor Bowser's office announced 1 more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \u201cessential,\u201d along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser\u2019s chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \u201cbecause construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\u201d<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toStay-at-home(link changed toStay-at-home order) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington,_D.C."}
{"title_page": "Nepalese Civil War", "text_new": "{{short description|1996\u20132006 civil war between the Nepalese government and a communist party}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Expert needed|date=May 2015}}\n{{POV check|date=January 2009}}\n{{More citations needed|date=May 2015}}}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Nepalese Civil War\n| image             = Ktm2006-malema.JPG\n| image_size        = 300px\n| caption           = Communist [[graffiti]] in [[Kathmandu]]. It reads: \"Long Live [[Marxism\u2013Leninism\u2013Maoism\u2013Prachanda Path|Marxism-Leninism-Maoism and Prachanda Path]]!\"\n| date              = 13 February 1996 \u2013 21 November 2006<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=13|year1=1996|month2=11|day2=21|year2=2006}})\n| place             = [[Nepal]]\n| casus             = [[Maoist]] opposition to the Nepali state\n| result            = [[Comprehensive Peace Accord]]\n* [[2008 Nepalese Constituent Assembly election|Constituent Assembly election]] held\n* Entry of [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist Centre)|Maoists]] into [[Politics of Nepal|mainstream politics]]\n* End of [[Monarchy of Nepal|240-year-long monarchy]]\n| combatant1        = {{flagicon|Nepal}} [[Kingdom of Nepal]]<br /> {{small|([[Politics of Nepal|Government of Nepal]])}}<br>\n* [[Royal Nepalese Army]]\n'''Supported by: '''<br />{{flagicon|United States}} [[United States]]<ref name=\"reliefweb\">{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/nepal/nepals-maoist-cauldron-draws-foreign-powers-closer|title=Nepal's Maoist cauldron draws foreign powers closer|last=Miglani|first=Sanjeev|date=18 August 2003|publisher=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529120217/https://reliefweb.int/report/nepal/nepals-maoist-cauldron-draws-foreign-powers-closer|archive-date=29 May 2018|url-status=}}</ref><br />{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/09/uk-covert-acts-maoists-nepal-civil-war-mi6-201491883138233479.html|title=UK's 'covert acts' during Nepalese civil war|first=Gyanu|last=Adhikari|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><br />{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.la-croix.com/Archives/2002-08-26/Une-polemique-eclate-en-Belgique-sur-une-vente-d-armes-au-Nepal-_NP_-2002-08-26-164179|title=Une pol\u00e9mique \u00e9clate en Belgique sur une vente d'armes au N\u00e9pal|newspaper=La Croix|date=26 August 2002|via=www.la-croix.com}}</ref><br />{{flagicon|China}} [[China]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/south_asia/4469508.stm|title=Chinese 'deliver arms to Nepal'|first=?|last=?|website=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><br />{{flagicon|India}} [[India]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/22/opinion/the-brutal-trap-of-nepals-civil-war.html|title=The brutal trap of Nepal's civil war|first=Peter|last=Bouckaert|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 October 2004}}</ref><br />{{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2006/01/mil-060123-irna03.htm|title=Nepal gov't procuring military articles from China, Pakistan|agency=IRNA|last=|website=globalsecurity.org}}</ref>\n| combatant2        = {{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)|Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]]<br />\n* [[People's Liberation Army, Nepal]]\n'''Supported by:'''<br />{{flagicon image|CPI-M-flag.svg}} [[Communist Party of India (Maoist)]]\n| commander1        = {{flagicon|Nepal}} '''[[King of Nepal]]''':<br />[[Birendra of Nepal|Birendra Bir Bikram Shah Dev]] ({{small|1972\u20132001)}}<br />[[Gyanendra of Nepal|Gyanendra Bir Bikram Shah Dev]] ({{small|2001\u201308)}}<br /> {{flagicon|Nepal}}''' [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]''':<br />[[Sher Bahadur Deuba]] ({{small|1995\u20131997; 2001\u201302; 2004\u201305}})<br />[[Lokendra Bahadur Chand]] ({{small|1997\u20131997; 2002\u201303}})<br />[[Surya Bahadur Thapa]] ({{small|1997\u20131998; 2003\u201304}})<br /> [[Girija Prasad Koirala]] ({{small|1998\u20131999; 2000\u201301; 2006\u201308}})<br />[[Krishna Prasad Bhattarai]] ({{small|1999\u20132000}})<br /> {{flagicon|Nepal}} '''[[Chief of Army Staff (Nepal)|COAS of the Nepalese Army]]:'''<br /> [[Dharmapaal Barsingh Thapa]] ({{small|1995\u20131999}}) <br /> Prajwalla Shumsher JBR ({{small|1999\u20132003}}) <br />[[Pyar Jung Thapa]] ({{small|2003\u20132006}}) <br />[[Rookmangud Katawal]] ({{small|2006\u20132009}})<br />{{flagicon|Nepal}} '''[[Inspector General of Police (Nepal)|IGP of Nepal Police]]:''' <br />[[Moti Lal Bohora]] ({{small|1992\u20131996}}) <br /> [[Achyut Krishna Kharel]] ({{small|1996\u20131996; 1996\u20131999}}) <br /> [[Dhruba Bahadur Pradhan]] ({{small|1996\u20131996}})<br /> [[Pradip Shumsher J.B.R.]] ({{small|1999\u20132002}})<br /> [[Shyam Bhakta Thapa]] ({{small|2002\u20132006}})<br />[[Om Bikram Rana]] ({{small|2006\u20132008}})\n| commander2        = {{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Prachanda]]<br />{{small|([[Pushpa Kamal Dahal]])}}\n<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Baburam Bhattarai]] ({{small|Laldhwaj}})\n<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Mohan Baidya]] {{small|(Kiran)}}\n<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Nanda Kishor Pun]]<br />{{small|(Pasang)}} \n<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} [[Ram Bahadur Thapa]]<br />{{small|(Badal)}}<ref name=\"nepalitimes\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/from-the-nepali-press/biplav-is-just-following-the-footsteps-of-mentors/|title=Biplav is just following the footsteps of mentors|first=Nepali|last=Times}}</ref><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of the Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist).svg}} Netra Bikram Chand<br />{{small|(Biplav)}}<ref name=\"nepalitimes\"/>\n| strength1         = \n| strength2         = \n| casualties1       = 4,500 killed<ref name=\"Douglas\">Ed Douglas. \"Inside Nepal's Revolution\". ''[[National Geographic Magazine]]'', p. 54, November 2005.</ref>\n| casualties2       = 8,200 killed <small>(guerrillas)</small><ref name=\"Douglas\"/>\n| casualties3       = 17,800 killed overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/nepal/17800-people-died-during-conflict-period-says-ministry-peace|title=17,800 people died during conflict period, says Ministry of Peace - Nepal|website=ReliefWeb}}</ref><br /> 1,300 missing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icmp.int/the-missing/where-are-the-missing/nepal/|title=ICMP Nepal|website=www.icmp.int}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Nepalese Civil War}}\n{{HistoryofNepal}}\nThe '''Nepalese Civil War''' (also known as the '''Maoist Conflict''' ({{lang-ne|\u092e\u093e\u0913\u0935\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u091c\u0928\u092f\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927}}; [[IAST]]: ''m\u0101ov\u0101d\u012b janayuddha''), the '''Maoist Insurgency''' or the '''Maoist Revolution''') was a [[civil war]] in [[Nepal]] fought between the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]] (CPN-M) and the [[government of Nepal]] from 1996 to 2006. The insurgency period is known as the '''Maovadi dwandakaal''' ({{lang-ne|\u092e\u093e\u0913\u0935\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u0926\u094d\u0935\u0928\u094d\u0926\u0915\u093e\u0932}}) in Nepal.\n\nThe rebellion was launched by the CPN-M on 13 February 1996 with the stated purpose of overthrowing the [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepalese monarchy]] and establishing a [[People's Republic]]. It ended with the signing of the [[Comprehensive Peace Accord]] on 21 November 2006. The conflict was characterized by summary [[execution]]s, [[massacres]], [[purges]], [[kidnapping]] and  other war crimes and [[crimes against humanity]]. The insurgency resulted in deaths of over 17,000 people including civilians, insurgents, army and police personnel, and internal displacement of hundreds of thousands of people (mostly of rural Nepal). According to INSEC, 1,665 of the dead were women.<ref name=\"Conflict Victim's Profile\">{{Cite web |title=Conflict Victim's Profile |publisher=INSEC |url=http://www.insec.org.np/victim/ |accessdate=3 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506170532/http://www.insec.org.np/victim/ |archive-date=6 May 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nOn 10 January 1990, the [[United Left Front (Nepal, 1990)|United Left Front (ULF)]] was formed,<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahadi\">{{cite book |author=Mahendra Lawoti and Anup K. Pahadi, editors |title=The Maoist Insurgency in Nepal: Revolution in the twenty-first century |year=2010 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-77717-9 }}</ref>{{rp|331}} which, together with the [[Nepali Congress]], was the backbone of the movement for democratic change. However, communist groups, uncomfortable with the alliance between the [[United Left Front (Nepal, 1990)|ULF]] and the [[Nepali Congress|Congress Party]], formed a parallel front, the [[United National People's Movement|United National People's Movement (UNPM)]]. The [[United National People's Movement|UNPM]] called for elections to a [[constituent assembly]], and rejected compromises made by [[United Left Front (Nepal, 1990)|ULF]] and the [[Nepali Congress|Congress Party]] with the royal house. In November 1990, the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unity Centre)]], or CPN(UC), was formed, and included key elements of the [[United National People's Movement|UNPM]]. On 21 January 1991, the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unity Centre)|CPN(UC)]] set up the [[United People's Front of Nepal|United People's Front of Nepal (UPFN)]], with [[Baburam Bhattarai]] as its head, as an open [[Front organization|front]] to contest elections.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\">{{cite book |author=Mahendra Lawoti and Anup K. Pahari, editors |title=The Maoist Insurgency in Nepal: Revolution in the twenty-first century |year=2010 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-77717-9 }}</ref>{{rp|332}} The [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unity Centre)|CPN(UC)]] held its first convention on 25 November 1991,<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|332}} adopted a line of \"protracted armed struggle on the route to a new democratic revolution\",<ref>{{cite book |author=Manesh Sreshtha and Bishnu Adhikari |title=Internal Displacement in South Asia: The Relevance of the UN's Guiding Principles |year=2005 |publisher=Sage |isbn=0-7619-3313-1}}</ref> and decided that the party would remain an underground party. In the [[1991 Nepalese legislative election|1991 election]], the [[United People's Front of Nepal|UPFN]] became the third-largest party in the [[Parliament of Nepal|Nepali parliament]]. However, disagreements within the [[United People's Front of Nepal|UPFN]] surged, regarding which tactics were to be used by the party. One group, led by [[Prachanda|Pushpa Kamal Dahal (alias Prachanda)]], argued for immediate armed revolution, while the other group, led by Nirmal Lama, claimed that Nepal was not yet ripe for armed struggle.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|332}}\n\nOn 22 May 1994, the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unity Centre)|CPN(UC)]]/[[United People's Front of Nepal|UPFN]] was split in two. The militant faction later renamed itself the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]], or CPN(M). This faction described the government forces, mainstream political parties, and the monarchy, as \"[[feudal]] forces\". The armed struggle began on 13 February 1996, when the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)|CPN(M)]] carried out 7 simultaneous attacks over 6 districts.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|333}} Initially, the Nepali government mobilized the [[Nepal Police]] to contain the insurgency. The [[Royal Nepal Army]] was not involved in direct fighting because the conflict was regarded as a policing matter. On Friday, 1 June 2001, there was a [[Nepalese royal massacre|massacre of the Nepalese royal family]] at the [[Narayanhiti Palace]] - the official residence of the [[Shah dynasty|House of Gorkha]], which was the royal house of Nepal at the time. Perpetrated by [[Dipendra Bir Bikram Shah|Prince Dipendra Bir Bikram Shah]], the heir apparent to the Nepalese thrown, there were ten deaths and five injuries - four injured victims and one self-inflicted injury on Dipendra after firing the weapon that he was using upon himself in the head as an apparent attempt at committing [[suicide]]. Dipendra's attempt against his own life initially failed as he fell into a coma for three days before dying, during which he was crowned as the new Nepalese king. On 25 July 2001, the government of [[Sher Bahadur Deuba]] and the Maoist insurgents declared a [[ceasefire]], and held peace talks from August to November of that year.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|335}} The failure of these peace talks resulted in the return to armed conflict, beginning with the Maoist attack on an army [[barracks]] in [[Dang Deokhuri District|Dang District]] in western Nepal, on 22 November.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|335}} The situation changed dramatically in 2002, as the number of attacks by both sides increased greatly, and more people died than in any other year of the war.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|309}}\n\nThe government responded by banning anti-monarchy statements,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Anti-king remarks intolerable: Lohani |publisher=NepalNews: The Kathmandu Post |date=20 December 2003 |url=http://www.nepalnews.com.np/contents/englishdaily/ktmpost/2003/dec/dec21/ |accessdate=22 November 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20041114013039/http://www.nepalnews.com.np/contents/englishdaily/ktmpost/2003/dec/dec21/ |archivedate = 14 November 2004}}</ref> imprisoning journalists, and shutting down newspapers accused of siding with the insurgents. Several rounds of negotiations, accompanied by temporary ceasefires, were held between the insurgents and the government. The government categorically rejected the insurgents' demand for the [[constituent assembly]] elections. At the same time, the Maoists refused to recognize the continued survival of [[constitutional monarchy]]. In November 2004, the government rejected both the Maoists' request to negotiate directly with [[King Gyanendra]] rather than via Prime Minister [[Sher Bahadur Deuba|Deuba]], and the Maoists' request for discussions to be mediated by a third party such as the United Nations.\n\nThroughout the war, the government controlled the main cities and towns, whilst the Maoists dominated the rural areas. In August 2004, the Maoists declared a week-long blockade of Kathmandu city which was later called off.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Maoist rebels call off Kathmandu blockade |publisher=The Guardian |date=24 August 2004 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/aug/24/nepal |accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 2005, in response to the inability of the relatively democratic government to restore order, [[King Gyanendra]] seized full control of Nepal in an attempt to definitively end the insurgency. He proclaimed, \"democracy and progress contradict one another... in pursuit of liberalism, we should never overlook an important aspect of our conduct, namely discipline.\"<ref>{{Cite web |title=Royal Proclamation of February 1, 2005 |publisher=Nepal Monarchy |date=4 May 2012 |url=http://www.nepalroyal.com/proclamationsfeb012005/ |accessdate=6 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016080039/http://www.nepalroyal.com/proclamationsfeb012005/ |archive-date=16 October 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> As a result of this takeover, the [[United Kingdom]] and [[India]] both suspended their material support for Nepal.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|337}} but China responded by dispatching arms to Nepal, in spite of the ideological affinity of the Maoists with China.<ref name=\"CI\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4469508.stm|title=BBC NEWS - South Asia - Chinese 'deliver arms to Nepal'|publisher=[[BBC]]]|date=25 November 2005|accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref> On 5 May 2005, in response to the takeover by [[King Gyanendra]], 7 political parties began talks to form a [[Seven Party Alliance|Seven Party Alliance (SPA)]].<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|338}} On 22 November 2005, with support from the [[Government of India|Indian government]], Maoist rebels and the [[Seven Party Alliance|SPA]] jointly issued a 12-point resolution, which described autocratic monarchy as the main obstacle to \"democracy, peace, prosperity, social upliftment and an independent and sovereign Nepal\",<ref>{{Cite web |title=12-point Maoist MoU |publisher=Nepali Times |date=25 November 2005 |url=http://nepalitimes.com/news.php?id=9190#.WlGCYijPxFQ |accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> and included a commitment to hold elections to a [[constituent assembly]] and for the Maoist rebels to renounce violence.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|339}}\n\nIn 2006, violent conflict decreased significantly, and instead, resistance transformed to non-violent pro-democracy demonstrations.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|339}}  Throughout April 2006, pro-democracy demonstrations were held across Nepal, and 19 demonstrators were killed, over 400 protesters were arrested, while dozens of others were injured. On 21 April, [[King Gyanendra]] announced that he would return governance to the [[Seven Party Alliance|SPA]], but this offer was rejected by both the Maoist rebels and the [[Seven Party Alliance|SPA]].<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|339}} On 24 April, [[King Gyanendra]] announced that he would also reinstate the [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]], which satisfied the [[Seven Party Alliance|SPA]], who formed the reinstated [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|339}} On 9 August, the government and the Maoist rebels agreed to accept the [[United Nations]] to monitor the peace process and to manage the arms of both sides.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|340}} On 21 November, the government, the [[Seven Party Alliance|SPA]], and the Maoist rebels signed the [[Comprehensive Peace Accord]], which formally ended the Civil War.<ref name=\"Lawoti-Pahari\" />{{rp|340}}\n\nThe Civil War forced young workers to seek work abroad, predominantly in the [[Persian Gulf]] and [[Southeast Asia|south-east Asia]]. The economy of Nepal is still heavily dependent on the infusion of foreign income from these migrant workers. As a result of the Civil War, Nepal's tourism industry suffered considerably.\n\n[[File:Maoist rebels on a hill in Nepal.jpg|thumb|right|Three [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)|Maoist]] rebels wait on top of a hill in the Rolpa district for orders to relocate]]\n\n==Army integration==\nThe [[Nepalese Army]] (NA) took final control over the [[People's Liberation Army (Nepal)|People's Liberation Army]] (PLA), the armed wing of the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist Centre)]], on 10 April 2012.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\">{{cite web|title=Nepal: Consolidating The Peace \u2013 Analysis|date=24 April 2012|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/24042012-nepal-consolidating-the-peace-analysis/|publisher=Eurasia Review|accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref> Prime Minister (PM) [[Baburam Bhattarai]], who also headed the Army Integration Special Committee (AISC), told the committee on 10 April 2012, that the NA was going to move into all 15 PLA cantonments, take full control, and take control of more than 3,000 weapons locked in containers there.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />  A total of 6,576 combatants chose the Voluntary Retirement Scheme (VRS), that promised cheques in the range of NPR 500,000 to NPR 800,000, depending on their rank.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />\n\nIn the first phase (18 November \u2013 1 December 2011) of regrouping, 9,705 former combatants had chosen integration into the NA.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />  In a landmark achievement, the AISC had initiated the process of integration following a 1 November 2011, seven-point deal signed by three major political parties \u2013 UCPN-M, [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)]] (CPN-UML) and [[Nepali Congress]] (NC) \u2013 and the umbrella formation of several Madheshi groups, the [[United Democratic Madhesi Front]] (UDMF).<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />  The deal provided three options to former PLA combatants \u2013 integration, voluntary retirement and rehabilitation.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> 9,705 combatants opted for integration, 7,286 chose voluntary discharge, and six combatants registered their names for rehabilitation packages.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> The [[United Nations Mission in Nepal]] (UNMIN) had registered 19,602 combatants in the second verification conducted on 26 May 2007.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />\n\nOn 14 April 2012, AISC decision laid down that the ranks of the integrated combatants would be determined according to the NA's, and not the PLA's, standards.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> A Selection Committee would be headed by the Chairman of Nepal's Public Service Commission (PSC) or by a member appointed by him, and a General Directorate would be created under the NA, headed by a Lieutenant General, to absorb the integrated combatants.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> The combatants will have to undergo between three and nine months of training, depending on their ranks.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> The Directorate would only be deployed for disaster relief, industrial security, development, and forest and environment conservation.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> On 17 April, the NA stated that it could not start the recruitment process of former Maoist combatants until the structure\u2014leadership and size\u2014of the General Directorate had been finalised at the political level.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" /> On 19 April 2012, the three major political parties agreed to merge two separate proposed commissions on Truth and Reconciliation, and on Disappearances, into one.<ref name=\"Nepal Eurasia Review\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n*'''13 February 1996''': Initiation of \"the people's war\" by the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]]\n*'''January 2001''': The government creates the [[Armed Police Force Nepal|Armed Police Force]], a Paramilitary force to fight the insurgents.\n*'''28 May 2001''': [[Prachanda|Chairman Prachanda]] gives an interview with the Communist journal ''[[Revolutionary Internationalist Movement|A World to Win]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=However tortuous the road may be, the victory of the world proletarian revolution is certain |publisher=Human Rights Server |date=28 May 2001 |url=http://www.humanrights.de/doc_en/archiv/n/nepal/politics/170202_interview_pra.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121143259/http://www.humanrights.de/doc_en/archiv/n/nepal/politics/170202_interview_pra.htm |archivedate=21 January 2016  }}</ref>\n*'''1 June 2001''': King [[Birendra of Nepal|Birendra]] and most of the royal family are killed in the [[Nepali royal massacre]]. Crown Prince Dipendra was accused of the massacre by the Incident Inquiry Committee consisting of Supreme Court Chief Justice Keshav Prasad Upadhaya, and the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Taranath Ranabhat. Dipendra, supposedly comatose after a [[suicide attempt]], is crowned king, according to tradition. He supposedly died on 4 June 2001, [[Gyanendra of Nepal|Gyanendra]] is crowned King.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenwald |first=Jeff |title=Murder and intrigue in Katmandu |publisher= World Tibet Network News |date=13 June 2001 |url=http://www.tibet.ca/en/wtnarchive/2001/6/13-2_3.html |accessdate=22 November 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060824142517/http://www.tibet.ca/en/wtnarchive/2001/6/13-2_3.html |archivedate = 24 August 2006}}</ref>\n*'''3 August 2001''': The first round of peace talks begin.\n*'''23 November 2001''': Peace talks collapse when the Maoists withdraw and launch a ferocious attack Police and Army posts in 42 districts.\n*'''26 November 2001''': The government of [[Sher Bahadur Deuba]] declares a Nationwide State of Emergency and deploys the [[Nepal Army]].<ref name=\"walkaway\">{{Cite web |last=Pokharel |first=Tilak P |title=Nepali Rebels Walk Away from Peace Talks |publisher=World Press |date=27 August 2003 |url=http://www.worldpress.org/Asia/1478.cfm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*US State Department declares Maoist political party as a terrorist organization. The [[United States Congress]] approves US$12 million to train [[Royal Nepal Army]] officers and supply 5,000 [[M16 rifle]]s.<ref name=\"reliefweb\"/>\n*'''May 2002''': Peace talks collapse.<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''May 2002''': Large battles fought between Army and Maoist forces at Lisne Lekh along the boundary between [[Pyuthan]] and [[Rolpa district]]s, and in Gam village, Rolpa.\n*'''22 May 2002''': [[King Gyanendra]], acting on the advice of Prime Minister [[Sher Bahadur Deuba]], dissolves Parliament and orders new elections. The reason given for the dissolution is opposition to the state of emergency.\n*'''11 July 2002''': Information leaks out that the Belgian weapon manufacturer [[FN Herstal]] is allowed to deliver 5,500 [[M249 Squad Automatic Weapon|M249 SAW]] light machine guns to the Nepali monarchy, a decision made by all coalition parties. Minister of External Affairs [[Louis Michel]] speaks of \"a country in a pluralistic democracy.\"\n*'''4 October 2002''': King Gyanendra deposes Prime Minister Deuba and the entire Council of Ministers, assumes executive power, and cancels the elections for the dissolved House of Representatives, which had been scheduled for '''11 November 2002'''.\n*'''11 October 2002''': King Gyanendra appoints [[Lokendra Bahadur Chand]] as Prime Minister.\n*'''January 2003''': The United States hold exercises with the Nepali army.<ref name=\"reliefweb\" /> Maoist insurgents kill the Inspector General of Armed Police, [[Krishna Mohan Shrestha]], his wife and his bodyguard, [[Head Constable]] Subhash Bahadur Gurung of the [[Armed Police Force Nepal]], while on their morning walk, as they used to do on Sunday mornings, intending to represent general safety to fellow citizens. The Inspector General and his wife, who was a teacher at an international school in the capital, were both unarmed. They were riddled with bullets from [[Type 56]] Rifles and [[Heckler & Koch G3|G3]] rifles used by the Maoists.\n*'''29 January 2003''': A second ceasefire is established and peace talks begin.<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''13 May 2003''': Code of conduct jointly declared by the government and the CPN-M for the mutually agreed period of cease-fire<ref>{{Cite web |last=Adhikari |first=Bipin |title=Code of conduct as a point of departure |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |date=19 March 2003 |url=http://www.nepalnews.com.np/contents/englishdaily/ktmpost/2003/mar/mar19/features1.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FR5LNAWo |archivedate=27 March 2013  }}</ref>\n*'''17 August 2003''': Nepali Military and Police forces kill 39 Maoist rebels in the [[Ramechhap]] District of central Nepal during an offensive launched jointly by the Army, Police, and Air Force of Nepal. 7 Soldiers of the Nepali Army and 5 Constables of the Armed Police are also killed in the operation.<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''24 August 2003''': The Maoists set an ultimatum, threatening to withdraw from the cease-fire if the government does not agree within 48 hours to include the question of the Maoists participating in the [[Constituent Assembly]].<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''26 August 2003''': The Maoist ultimatum expires.<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''27 August 2003''':\n**Strike: The Maoist call for a three-day strike to denounce the Army's attacks on their cadres<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n**The Maoists unilaterally withdraw from 29 January [[cease-fire]]. Prachanda's statement revives the rebels' demand for an end to monarchic rule in favor of a \"people's republic\", stating, \"Since the old regime has put an end to the forward-looking solution to all existing problems through the ceasefire and peace talks, we herein declare that the rationale behind ceasefire...and peace process has ended.\"<ref name=\"walkaway\" />\n*'''28 August 2003''': Maoist hitmen shoot two colonels of the Royal Nepal Army in their homes in Kathmandu, killing one and injuring the other.<ref>NEPAL: MAOIST HIT TEAMS SHOOT TWO ARMY COLONELS IN KATHMANDU https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/03KATHMANDU1648_a.html</ref>\n*'''29 August 2003''': Maoist insurgents unsuccessfully attempt to assassinate a Devendra Raj Kandel, a Nepali minister.<ref name=\"wikileaks.org\">UPDATE ON NEPAL'S MAOIST INSURGENCY, 30 AUGUST \u2013 5 September https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/03KATHMANDU1721_a.html</ref>\n*'''31 August 2003''': Maoist insurgents ambush a Nepalese police outpost in Rupandehi, killing 4 policemen.<ref name=\"wikileaks.org\"/>\n*'''2 September 2003''':  Maoist insurgents ambush a Nepalese police outpost in Siraha, killing 2 policemen and injuring four others.<ref name=\"wikileaks.org\"/>\n*'''27 September 2003''': \"Fifteen people including 8 Rebels and 4 Policemen were killed and suspected Maoists bombed five government utilities despite the guerrillas' plans for a nine-day truce from '''2 October 2003''', officials said. Eight Maoists were killed in a gun battle with security forces at Chhita Pokhara in the [[Khotang District]], 340 kilometres east of [[Kathmandu]], a police officer said. 4 Policemen were also killed. Elsewhere in eastern Nepal, the Maoists killed two Policemen, Constable Purna Prasad Sharma and Head Constable Radha Krishna [[Gurung]], and a woman selling beetle nuts, Kali Tamang, in the Jaljale-Gaighat area, an official said. 'A group of seven Maoists descended from a public bus when police were checking the passengers and suddenly opened fire from an automatic pistol, killing the three and wounding two others,' said Sitaram Prasad Pokharel, the chief administrator for the region. In [[Janakpur]], an industrial hub on the Indian border 260 kilometres south-east of Kathmandu, the Maoists under the direct command of [[Prachanda]] carried out five early morning bombings that disrupted telephone service and power, police said. No one was killed directly by the blasts but an elderly man died of a heart attack after hearing the explosions, Police Deputy Superintendent Bharat Chhetri said. He said the sites that were bombed included the offices of the roads department and the Nepal Electricity Authority and a telecommunications tower. Police personnel and Maoists traded fire for nearly 40 minutes after the blasts but the rebels escaped and 37 people were injured, Mr Khadka said.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title=More die in Nepal Maoist insurgency despite truce call |publisher=ABC News Online |date=28 September 2003 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s955264.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031003184150/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s955264.htm |archivedate=3 October 2003 }}</ref>\n*'''13 October 2003''': At least 42 Police Recruits and 9 Maoists are killed when an estimated 3,000 Maoists attempt to storm a Police Training Center in Bhaluwang. \"'The rebels had snapped telephone cables, set up roadblocks by felling trees or blowing up highway bridges to prevent reinforcements from coming,' a witness, Krishna Adhikary, told Reuters.\"<ref>{{Cite web |title=37 killed as Maoist army attacks camp |publisher=The Telegraph |date=14 October 2003 |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1031014/asp/foreign/story_2458810.asp }}</ref>\n*'''27 October 2003''': \" Colonel Adrian Griffith and six Nepali nationals were freed last week 42 hours after being taken captive in [[Baglung]], {{convert|300|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of Kathmandu, while on a drive to recruit young Gurkha soldiers to serve in the British army.\" Party chief [[Prachanda]] said, \"We are sorry for the incident that took place against the policy of the party.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Sushil |title=Maoists 'sorry' UK officer held |publisher=BBC News |date=27 October 2003 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3216993.stm }}</ref>\n*'''11 November 2003''': The government Defence Ministry accuses the Maoists of abducting twenty-nine 9th- and 10th-grade students from Riva Secondary School in [[Mugu District]], western Nepal during the previous week.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How anti-monarchy movement took shape |work=The Independent  |url=http://independent-bangladesh.com/news/apr/27/27042006re.htm#A2 }}</ref>\n*'''15 November 2003''': Four police officers, including Kamalapati Pant (Nepal Police Force), were shot dead from behind on a tea shop by two armed Maoist rebel who approached in Motorcycle & fled away immediately, in [[Nepalgunj]].\n*'''19 November 2003''': According to a Nepal army official, four people were caught at the Chinese Khasa border point, 114 kilometers northeast of Kathmandu, smuggling weapons from [[Tibet]] into Nepal. The official named Hirala Lal Shrestha and Gyaljen Sherpa and said they were taken for interrogation in the Tibetan town of [[Xigatse]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=China arrests four Nepali Maoists for arms smuggling |work=Daily News |date=20 November 2003 |url=http://www.jang.com.pk/thenews/nov2003-daily/19-11-2003/world/w2.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031206173448/http://jang.com.pk/thenews/nov2003-daily/19-11-2003/world/w2.htm |archivedate=6 December 2003 }}</ref>\n\n===2004===\n*'''5 February 2004''': An Army raid is carried out by the [[Bhairavnath Battalion]] on a village in Bhimad, [[Makwanpur District]]. Reports emerge that 14 suspected Maoist rebels and two civilians were executed after being captured. [[Amnesty International]] later wrote a letter to Prime Minister [[Surya Bahadur Thapa]] and Brigadier-General Nilendra Aryal, Head of the [[Royal Nepal Army]] (RNA) human rights cell, demanding an immediate inquiry.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nepal: Extra-judicial killings inquiry urgent |publisher=Scoop |date=18 February 2004 |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO0402/S00154.htm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*'''10 February 2004''': Two central committee members of the CPN-M, Matrika Yadav and Suresh Paswan, are reported to have been handed over by India to Nepal. They were reportedly arrested in [[Lucknow]] after Nepal provided information.<ref>{{Cite web |title=India hands over two Maoist leaders to Nepal |work=The Times of India  |date=10 February 2004 |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2004-02-10/india/28326314_1_matrika-yadav-maoist-leaders-radio-nepal }}</ref>\n*'''13 February 2004''': Ganesh Chilwal leads an anti-Maoist protest on this day, the eighth anniversary of the commencement of the revolution.<ref name=\"anti-rebel\">{{cite news |title=Nepal anti-rebel leader shot dead |publisher=BBC News |date=15 February 2004 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3490725.stm }}</ref>\n*'''15 February 2004''': Ganesh Chilwal is shot dead in his Kathmandu office by two suspected Maoists.<ref name=\"anti-rebel\" />\n*'''15 February 2004''': Fighting erupts at a Maoist jungle base in [[Kalikot District]], 360&nbsp;km west of [[Kathmandu]]. The base is said to hold 5000 Maoist troops. On '''17 February 2004''', a security official says that a private helicopter flying troops to Kalikot was hit by Maoist fire but that it returned safely to Kathmandu. On '''18 February 2004''', 65 Maoists are reported to have been killed, though this conflicts with other reported death tolls of 35 and 48.<ref name=\"kurakani\">{{Cite web |title=48 Maoist rebels killed in Nepal army attacks |publisher=KuraKani |date=17 February 2004 |url=http://www.kurakani.tk/Article163.phtml }}</ref>\n*'''15 February and 16 2004''': Nepalese state radio reports that 13 Maoist rebels were killed in seven separate small clashes with security forces across the country.<ref name=\"kurakani\" />\n*'''18 February 2004''': Lawmaker Khem Narayan Faujdar, a member of the parliament dissolved by [[King Gyanendra]] in 2002, is shot dead by two suspected Maoists riding a motorcycle in the [[Nawalparasi District]], 200&nbsp;km southwest of the capital, according to the police.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chronology of decade-long conflict |publisher=ReliefWeb |date=22 November 2006 |url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/VBOL-6VSKJU?OpenDocument&RSS20=02-P }}</ref>\n*'''2 April 2004''': The largest rallies since 1990 begin in Kathmandu. They are variously labelled \"pro-democracy\" and \"anti-monarchy.\"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sharma |first=Gopal |title=Nepal parties plan anti-monarchy rally |publisher=Independent Online |date=9 April 2004 |url=http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=3&art_id=qw1081491841355B251 }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web |title=140 Injured As Clashes Rock Nepal's Capital |publisher=INDOlink |date=5 April 2004 |url=http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=040404100829 |access-date=27 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303222419/http://www.indolink.com/displayArticleS.php?id=040404100829 |archive-date=3 March 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n*'''3 April 2004''': More than 12 trucks are burnt while waiting at a western Nepal border post to pick up petrol from India. India condemns the attacks and vows to fight terrorism.<ref name=\"utusan\">{{Cite web |title=Maoist rebels storm police post in Nepal, kill 9 |publisher=Utusan Online |date=5 April 2004 |url=http://www.utusan.com.my/utusan/content.asp?y=2004&dt=0406&pub=Utusan_Express&sec=World&pg=wo_05.htm }}</ref>\n*'''4 April 2004''': \"Some 150 demonstrators were struck during a police [[baton charge]]\" during demonstrations in Kathmandu<ref>{{Cite web |title=9 policemen dead as Maoists storm post in Nepal |publisher=INQ7 |date=5 April 2004 |url=http://www.inq7.net/wnw/2004/apr/06/wnw_4-1.htm }}</ref>\n*'''4 April 2004''': \"Hundreds of Maoist rebels\" attack a Police outpost in Yadukuwa, Jadukhola. 13 policemen are killed, 7 wounded, and 35 are listed as missing. 8\u20139 Maoists are also killed. \"Witnesses said more than 500 rebels attacked the Police post and began firing Assault Rifles and [[RPG-7]] rockets. at around 9&nbsp;pm (1515 GMT) on Sunday night. The fighting lasted two to three hours.\"  Other reports state 400 rebels.<ref name=\"utusan\" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Rebels storm police post, kill nine officers |publisher=Gulfnews |date=6 April 2004 |url=http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/04/04/06/117143.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612175452/http://archive.gulfnews.com/articles/04/04/06/117143.html |archivedate=12 June 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Maoists kill 9 policemen |publisher=The Telegraph |date=5 April 2004 |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1040406/asp/foreign/story_3092324.asp }}</ref>\n*'''4 April 2004''': In the west of the country three Indian traders are shot and injured and have their vehicles burned.<ref name=\"utusan\" />\n*'''5 April 2004''': A three-day national strike begins, called by CPN(M) and opposed by an \"alliance of five political parties\" who are protesting in Kathmandu against the monarchy and say the strike will hamper the movement of demonstrators in Kathmandu. [[Prachanda]] said, \"The time has come to win a united struggle against the feudal forces as the king is trying to take the nation back to the 18th century.\"<ref>{{Cite web |last=Singh |first=Kedar Man |title=Anti-monarchy protesters pack streets of Kathmandu |publisher=INQ7 |date=3 April 2004 |url=http://www.inq7.net/wnw/2004/apr/04/wnw_3-2.htm }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title= Major parties take to the streets in Nepal |newspaper=The Hindu  |date=14 March 2004 |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/03/15/stories/2005031503781400.htm }}</ref>\n*'''5 April 2004''': In the morning, 3 soldiers are killed and 7 injured by a CPN(M) landmine activated by their vehicle at Dhalkhola, 50&nbsp;km east of Kathmandu.<ref name=\"utusan\" />\n*'''5 April 2004''': At least 140 people are injured in clashes in Kathmandu as \"about 50,000\" demonstrators confront the police. Demonstrators try to break through a police barricade close to the royal palace. The police respond with tear gas and protesters are reportedly injured by police batons. Rocks and bricks are thrown by both sides. Demonstrations also occur in [[Patan, Lalitpur|Lalitpur]] and [[Bhaktapur]]. Meanwhile, [[king Gyanendra]] has reportedly been away touring villages in western Nepal.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n*'''5 April 2004''': The Indian government announces that it will no longer provide police escorts to Indian officials shopping in Nepal, as a means to discourage such trips. Fears are based on the CPN(M) targeting Indians. \"We are worried about possible reprisals here if the Maoists continue to target Indians inside Nepal,\" said a senior police official.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Police want 'shopping trip' slowdown in Nepal |work=The Statesman |location=India |date=5 April 2004 |url=http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=2&id=68320&usrsess=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612210430/http://www.thestatesman.net/page.arcview.php?clid=2&id=68320&usrsess=1 |archivedate=12 June 2008 }}</ref>\n*'''24 June 2004''': The nephew of former Prime Minister [[Surya Bahadur Thapa]] is hacked to death by Maoist insurgents in [[Dhankuta District]].<ref>MAOIST ATROCITIES ESCALATE, 5 JUNE-PRESENT https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/04KATHMANDU1672_a.html</ref>\n*'''16 August 2004''': The Soaltee Hotel, a popular luxury hotel in Kathmandu, is bombed, after refusing a demand from the Maoists that the hotel close.[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/maoist-bicycle-bomber-attacks-luxury-hotel-in-capital-of-nepal-1.1153654?mode=amp Maoist bicycle bomber attacks luxury hotel in capital of Nepal]\n*'''18 August 2004''': A bomb explodes in a marketplace in southern Nepal. The blast kills a 12-year-old boy and wounds six others, including three policemen. In addition, Maoist rebels, demanding the release of captured guerrillas, stop all road traffic near Kathmandu by threatening to attack vehicles. Some Nepal businesses are shut down because of threats.\n*'''10 September 2004''': A bomb explodes at the [[United States Information Service]] office in Kathmandu.\n*'''13 September 2004''': U.S. Peace Corps suspends operations and non-essential U.S. Embassy personnel are evacuated from Nepal.\n*'''9 November 2004''': 36 people were injured when suspected Maoist rebels exploded a powerful bomb at an under-construction government office complex, the Karmachari Sanchaya Kosh Office Complex in the heart of Nepalese capital Kathmandu Tuesday.\n*'''11 November 2004''': Maoists kill NID Deputy Superintendent of Police Hemraj Regmi in front of his office residence in Butwal municipality-6 in Rupandehi district.\n*'''15 December 2004''': Twenty government security personnel are killed in the western district of [[Arghakhanchi District|Arghakhanchi]] when the Maoists mount a surprise attack.[[File:DSP Hem Raj Regmi Shot dead by Maoist.jpg|thumb|In the Offensive: DSP Hem Raj Regmi was shot dead by Maoists, '''11 November 2004''']]\n*'''16 December 2004''': Sixteen Maoist rebels are killed in clashes with Nepali security forces in the western district of [[Dailekh District|Dailekh]].\n*'''23 December 2004''': Maoist forces launch blockade of Kathmandu.\n*'''26 December 2004''': Over 15,000 hold peace rally in Kathmandu.\n\n===2005===\n*'''2 January 2005''': Nepali media reports two children being killed in [[Dailekh District]] by a Maoist bomb.\n*'''4 January 2005''': Three government security personnel and between two and twenty-four Maoist rebels reported killed in fighting.\n*'''8 January 2005''': Maoists detain and later release 300 passengers from six buses that defy their blockade of Kathmandu.\n*'''10 January 2005''': Prime Minister Deuba said he would increase defense spending to fight the Maoists unless they come forward for talks with the government.\n*'''11 January 2005''': Protests and blockades over the government fuel price increases of between 10% and 25%.\n*'''15 January 2005''': Maoists allegedly detain 14 Indian Gurkhas from Chuha village in [[Kailali]].\n*'''29 January 2005''': Government leader in the Lamjung district had been abducted and murdered with a gunshot to the head.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nepalconflictreport.ohchr.org/html/incidents/2005-01-29_incident_lamjung_insec-2010.html|title=2005-01-29 - incident - Lamjung district {{!}} \u0968\u0966\u096c\u0967-\u0967\u0966-\u0967\u096c - \u0918\u091f\u0928\u093e - \u0932\u092e\u091c\u0941\u0919 \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e|website=nepalconflictreport.ohchr.org|language=en|access-date=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n*'''1 February 2005''': King Gyanendra dissolves the Deuba government and bans all news reports. The army begins arresting senior political leaders, journalists, trade unionists, human rights activists and civil society leaders. All telephone and internet connections are cut.\n*'''6 June 2005''': [[Badarmude bus explosion]]: Some 38 civilians are killed and over 70 injured after a packed passenger bus runs over a rebel landmine in [[Chitwan District]].\n*'''9 August 2005''': Maoist rebels kill 40 security men in midwestern Nepal.\n*'''3 September 2005''': The Maoists declare a three-month unilateral ceasefire to woo opposition political parties.\n*'''19 November 2005''': After negotiations, the Maoist rebels agree to work with opposition politicians in a common front against the rule of King [[Gyanendra of Nepal]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nepal rebels ready to surrender under UN supervision |work=The Times of India  |date=20 November 2005 |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-11-20/rest-of-world/27833882_1_maoist-rebels-nepal-rebels-king-gyanendra |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718131729/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-11-20/rest-of-world/27833882_1_maoist-rebels-nepal-rebels-king-gyanendra |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Sharma |first=Nagendar |title=Nepal opposition in Maoist talks |publisher=BBC News |date=18 November 2005 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4450438.stm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===2006===\n[[File:Jana andolan.jpg|thumb|right|250px|2006 democracy movement]]\n*'''2 January 2006''': Rebels decide not to extend a four-month ceasefire saying that the government had broken the ceasefire with numerous attacks on Maoist villages.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pasricha |first=Anjana |title=Nepal Rebels Call Off Four-Month Truce |publisher=Voice of America |date=2 January 2006 |url=http://www.voanews.com/english/archive/2006-01/2006-01-02-voa14.cfm?CFID=3777224&CFTOKEN=93126810 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20060207185332/http://voanews.com/english/archive/2006-01/2006-01-02-voa14.cfm?CFID=24594161&CFTOKEN=12401453 |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 February 2006 |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*'''14 January 2006''': Maoists launch coordinated attacks of five military and paramilitary targets in the [[Kathmandu Valley]]. The first demonstration of their ability to organize violence within the Valley, prompting curfews at night for the next several days.\n*'''14 March 2006''': Nepali rebels extend road blockade; nationwide strike called for '''3 April 2006'''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nepal rebels call for indefinite strike against king |work=The Boston Globe |date=18 February 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2006/02/18/nepal_rebels_call_for_indefinite_strike_against_king/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725150841/http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2006/02/18/nepal_rebels_call_for_indefinite_strike_against_king/ |archivedate=25 July 2012 }}</ref>\n*'''5 April 2006''': [[2006 democracy movement in Nepal#April general strike|General strike]] begins with Maoist forces promising to refrain from violence.\n*'''6 April 7, 2006''': Protesters clash with police, hundreds arrested, dozens injured.\n*'''8 April 2006''': A [[curfew]] is imposed in Kathmandu from 10&nbsp;pm to 9&nbsp;am The king orders protesters violating the curfew to be \"shot on sight.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Gurubacharya |first=Binaj |title=Anti-monarchy rallies spread in Nepal |work=The Boston Globe |date=8 April 2006 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2006/04/08/anti_monarchy_rallies_spread_in_nepal/ }}{{dead link|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n*'''9 April 2006''': General strike scheduled to end. Government extends curfew, [[BBC]] reports. Three dead in two days of unrest, as thousands of demonstrators defy curfews.<ref>{{cite news |title=Violent clashes amid Nepal curfew |publisher=BBC News |date=10 April 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4894474.stm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*'''26 April 2006''': they started to unblock streets and roads, but they had some conditions\n*'''27 April 2006''': Maoist insurgents, responding to a demand by the newly appointed Prime Minister [[Girija Prasad Koirala]], announce a unilateral three-month [[truce]] after [[2006 democracy movement in Nepal|weeks of pro-democracy protests]] in Kathmandu, and encourage the formation of a new constituent assembly tasked with rewriting the nation's constitution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nepal Maoist rebels declare truce |publisher=BBC News |date=27 April 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4949066.stm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Nepal's Maoists Declare Ceasefire |publisher=Voice of America |date=27 April 2006 |url=http://voanews.com/english/archive/2006-04/nepal-ceasfire.cfm?CFID=3777874&CFTOKEN=10318971 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20081215040722/http://voanews.com/english/archive/2006-04/nepal-ceasfire.cfm?CFID=3777874&CFTOKEN=10318971 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 December 2008 |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*'''3 May 2006''': Nepal's new cabinet declares a ceasefire. This was not taken very seriously. The cabinet also announces that the Maoist rebels will no longer be considered a terrorist group. Rebels are also encouraged to open peace talks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nepal calls ceasefire with rebels |publisher=BBC News |date=3 May 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4969422.stm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*'''21 November 2006''': Peace talks end with the signing of the [[Comprehensive Peace Accord]] between Prime Minister Koirala and Maoist leader Prachanda. The deal allows the Maoists to take part in government, and places their weapons under UN monitoring.<ref>{{cite news |title=Peace deal ends Nepal's civil war |publisher=BBC News |date=21 November 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6169746.stm |accessdate=22 November 2006 }}</ref>\n*Maoists affirm that they control the 80% of the countryside territories, and that they have people infiltrated also in the urban areas.\n\n==Aftermath==\nMore than 17,000 people (including both civilians and armed forces) were killed during the conflict, including over 4,000 Nepalis killed by Maoists from 1996\u20132005, and over 8,200 Nepalis killed by government forces from 1996\u20132005.<ref name=\"Douglas\"/> In addition, an estimated 100,000 to 150,000 people were [[internally displaced]] as a result of the conflict. Furthermore, this conflict disrupted most [[rural development]] activities.\n\nIn July 2007, the Ministry of Peace and Reconstruction proposed legislation that would establish a [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] in Nepal.<ref>[http://ictj.org/selecting-commissioners-nepal Selecting Commissioners for Nepal's Truth and Reconciliation Commission] ''International Center for Transitional Justice (ICTJ)</ref> The parliament set up a Truth and Reconciliation Commission to investigate wartime killings, torture and forced disappearances and debated proposals to grant an amnesty for abuses by government and rebel forces.\nThe \"revolution\" resulted in political, social and cultural change in Nepal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://therisingnepal.org.np/news/2941|title=The Rising Nepal: The Maoist Movement On Terminal Decline?: Ritu Raj Subedi|website=therisingnepal.org.np}}</ref><ref>https://www.kantipurdaily.com/opinion/2013/02/18/362814.html</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://ehimalayatimes.com/bichar-sahitya/16264 | title=\u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0940 \u0938\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0915\u0943\u0924\u093f\u092e\u093e \u0915\u094d\u0930\u092e\u092d\u0919\u094d\u0917 | date=12 August 2017 | publisher=ehimalayatimes.com | accessdate=20 February 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[[Women in the Nepalese Civil War]]\n*[[Military of Nepal]]\n*[[Murder of Maina Sunuwar]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Hutt, Michael, ''Himalayan People's War: Nepal's Maoist Rebellion,'' (London: Hurst and Co., 2004) {{ISBN|978-0-253-21742-4}}.\n*[[doi:10.1080/02684527.2019.1589677|Jackson, Paul. 2019. \"Intelligence in a modern insurgency: the case of the Maoist insurgency in Nepal.\"  ''Intelligence and National Security''.]]\n*Karki, Arjun and David Seddon (eds.), ''The People's War in Nepal: Left Perspectives,'' (New Delhi: Adroit, 2003).\n*Thapa, Deepak, with Bandita Sijapati, ''A Kingdom Under Siege: Nepal's Maoist Insurgency, 1996\u20132003,'' (Kathmandu: The Printhouse, 2003) {{ISBN|978-1-842-77571-4}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://interactive.aljazeera.com/aje/2016/nepal-maoist-dream Nepal's civil war and its subsequent democratic transition] by [[Al Jazeera]]\n* [https://www.ictj.org/our-work/regions-and-countries/nepal International Center for Transitional Justice, Nepal]\n*[http://peacemaker.un.